<h2 id="renting-an-arma-3-server-vs-hosting-your-own">Renting an Arma 3 Server vs Hosting Your Own</h2>

<p>You <em>can</em> host your own Arma 3 server on your PC, although I‚Äôd highly recommend you rent a server instead.</p>

<p>Here‚Äôs why:</p>

<p>Arma 3 isn‚Äôt optimized well in the first place. Even top-tier gaming PCs have trouble breaking 60 FPS at max settings, not to mention the extra demand required by mods.</p>

<p>Notoriously CPU intensive, Arma 3 sucks the power out of your rig. The huge map, projectile simulation, and high slot servers consume your CPU power faster than the fat lady down the road can pound a Big Mac.</p>

<p>Hosting a server at the same time? Forget about it.</p>

<p>On top of having to run the game (which is hard enough), your PC now has to host the entire server at the same time. That means keeping track of everything, everyone, and more.</p>

<p>If you thought Arma 3 was laggy before, try hosting a server and playing at the same time. Now, you <em>and</em> everyone else on the server will lag too, since they‚Äôre depending on your computer‚Äôs already so-so performance.</p>

<p>Hosting a dedicated server on your PC for a game like <a href="/game-hosts/terraria/">Terraria</a> is different. Terraria isn‚Äôt very intensive on its own (it‚Äôs 2D), and having a few friends on your server isn‚Äôt intensive either.</p>

<p>But the more assets and players on the server, the more resource intensive it becomes. Arma 3 is one of the most demanding games on Steam, and hosting a server is pretty intensive too.</p>

<p>What‚Äôs the bottom line here?</p>

<p>Renting an Arma 3 server from a hosting company is your best bet.</p>

